entry.title: Exclude two more NOTREACHED()s
entry.content:
The NOTREACHED() hit in extensions/renderer/dispatcher.cc was found as

we're seeing an increase in the extensions::ScriptContext::RunScript

signature but parts of the stack was ICF'd (where the NOTREACHED()

actually got hit).



To find this one we searched for all crash reports containing

extensions::ScriptContext::RunScript on the stack and then looking at

the error-message field. This essentially let us find if the

NOTREACHED() hit was ever reported in a build where NOTREACHED() logging

has not been optimized out, and if so which non-code-folded path hit it.



There was another hit instance for extensions::ScriptContext::RunScript

in extensions/renderer/api/web_request_hooks.cc but it has already been

marked DUMP_WILL_BE_NOTREACHED_NORETURN().

entry.title: [OOPIF PDF] Always allow PDF frames to execute JavaScript
entry.content:
Always allow PDF frames to execute JavaScript, even when the JavaScript

content setting is disabled.



In order for the Chrome PDF viewer to load, The PDF extension frame and

the PDF content frame need to run JavaScript. Explicitly allow these two

frames to execute JavaScript.



Note that setting a custom scope for content settings is insufficient

for letting the PDF viewer to load. While the PDF extension origin is

trusted and can be allowlisted, the PDF content frame has the same

origin as the PDF embedder frame, which is untrusted and should not be

allowlisted. Instead, directly set the content setting in the

content::NavigationHandle.

entry.title: Revert "[Android TRM] Implement better result stability check."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 918dcbe5a3bd443816093e94c75ace75a0dff04a.



Reason for revert: The INIT-TENTATIVE-STABLE model misses the

following cases:

* Init something --> (long wait) Sync disable:

In this case, sync disable would trigger call to loadModule(). Now

|mModuleStage = TENTATIVE|, but logistically it should be STABLE

(and in the future, logged as "something")

* Init any --> something --> nothing:

The final "nothing" was assumed in the CL to be permission changes.

However, it can also be suggestion change (triggered by a

different NTP). In this case we don't want UI to change.



Therefore more needs to be done to determine:

* When a "update call" is stale.

* Discerning "nothing" coming from permission change or not.



The CL was landed shortly after M124 branch. We'd like to make a fix

and merge it. To reduce churn, we'll just revert the CL and land a

new fix, instead of building on top of this (and needing to merge

twice).



Original change's description:

> [Android TRM] Implement better result stability check.

>

> crrev.com/c/5366274 fixed Tab Resumption Module's the general lag issue

> by letting "fast path" fetching "nothing" put the Mediator into a

> "tentatively gone" state, under which "slow path" fetching "something"

> can cause the module to show.

>

> Previously, ForeignSessionTabResumptionDataProvider may fire "something"

> via "slow path" many times, until a 10s of inactivity is reached, after

> which the provider is declared stable and the TRM no longer change

> (except to disappear on permission changes). This allowed the TRM to

> fetch the freshest results at initialization. However, this also makes

> it hard to decide, from the Provider's perspective, when results becomes

> stable -- this will be needed for upcoming effort to gather metrics.

>

> This CL fixes the problem by revamping how the TRM reaches stability.

> Details:

> * TabResumptionDataProvider: Add |mIsStable| flag with write accessor.

> * ForeignSessionTabResumptionDataProvider: Remove time-based stability

> detection; simply use |mIsStable|.

> * Mediator:

> * Revamp state machine: Decompose it into a direct product of:

> * mModuleStage in {INIT, TENTATIVE, STABLE}.

> * mDoShow in {false, true}.

> * Extract setPropertiesAndTriggerRender().

> * Extract onSuggestionReceived() for loadModule(), and change state

> transition mechanics:

> * Use simple progression INIT -> TENTATIVE -> STABLE (terminal).

entry.title: Add experimental command for sending pending Attribution Reports
entry.content:
As part of the normal API operation, Attribution Reports are sent with

delays up to 30 days. The Attribution Internals API already exposes the

ability to send pending reports immediately to facilitate manual

testing; this change provides similar functionality to DevTools without

exposing individual reports to the API, in order to account for

forthcoming storage changes in which reports are not individually

identifiable while pending. Sending *all* pending reports should be

sufficient for our use cases.



Unfortunately, it is somewhat difficult to arrange for the web tests

to check that the reports are actually sent, i.e. by arranging for

a server to record requests received at the API's well-known URL as

we do in our regular web platform tests. We can investigate adding

such coverage in the future.

entry.title: Prepare to convert SBThreatType to an enum class in /chrome/browser/webshare
entry.content:
It's somewhat difficult to log an SBThreatType as an UMA histogram since

we don't have a kMaxValue. We can't simply add a kMaxValue because

SBThreatType is an enum instead of enum class, and we'd be exposing a

constant safe_browsing::kMaxValue. This CL prepares to convert

SBThreatType to an enum class in /chrome/browser/webshare.



That requires two changes:



- SBThreatType is no longer implicitly convertible to int, so we will

need a few static casts



- SBThreatType values are now in the namespace

safe_browsing::SBThreatType instead of just safe_browsing. In some

places this is fixed by adding the new namespace, and in some places

with a "using enum" declaration. We can't just add a "using enum" for

all usages of SBThreatType because "using enum" would declare a

constant kMaxValue. So "using enum" is only used when many

SBThreatType constants are used, and in as narrow a scope as possible.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.

entry.title: Reland: [A11y] Small simplification to ignored computation for block flows
entry.content:
Originally CL:4261382.

Was reverted because of https://issues.chromium.org/issues/40912725.

accessibility.WebContentsAccessibilityTreeTest#test_fixedWidthText



This continues the work from CL:4194697 to simplify our code that

decides whether or not a block flow is ignored. By simplifying, we

improve performance and predictability, and have fewer cases where

we miss an invalidation when one of the dependent conditions changes.



In this case, we remove code that checks to see if a cursor can be

set inside of the block flow. As a result, a few more harmless

generic containers are introduced to the hierarchy. It is not

necessary to remove all uninteresting generic containers, and it is

only an optimization to do so. In this case, the extra "magic"

regarding Cursor is not worth having a few extra generic

containers in the tree.



The code is now clearer and less likely to run into a state where

there is a stale tree structure containing a node with the wrong

ignored state, confusing the serializer.

entry.title: [Extensions][DNR] Fix prefs deletion for delayed installs
entry.content:
In PopulateExtensionInfoPrefs, certain prefs are supposed to be removed

from the extension_dict. This works fine if extension_dict points

directly to the extension's own prefs, but these prefs are not

removed if it points to a dict for delayed install prefs that are

meant to be applied to the extension's own prefs later (since delayed

install prefs are created from scratch).



To fix this, add a removed_prefs list which stores pref keys that

will actually be removed when a delayed installation is completed.



This was found to be the root cause of the DNR bug found below, and

a regression test was added.



Note: While this fix prevents this issue from popping up again, it

cannot fix corrupted/stale prefs with values from a previous version

of the extension that were not cleaned up for a delayed install or

update.



For the kDNRStaticRulesetPref, this was fixed by incrementing the

ruleset format version which forces a re-index which will write the

correct values to prefs.



The extension just needs to call the

declarativeNetRequest.UpdateEnabledStaticRulesets method to correct

the value of the kDNREnabledStaticRulesetIDs pref.

entry.title: Mojo: Represent maps with int64/uint64 keys as Maps in JS/TS
entry.content:
Mojo bindings code decodes maps for JS/TS in 2 different ways:

(1) as object maps (i.e. {[key: KeyType]: ValueType})

(2) as JS Maps (i.e. Map)

This is based on whether the KeyType is marked as

isValidObjectKeyType.



Previously, int64/uint64 had isValidObjectKeyType: true, so maps with

these mojo types as the key were decoded as object maps in JS/TS.

However, int64/uint64 map to the JS BigInt type. Comments in the JS/TS

generators note that BigInts should not be allowed as Object map keys

and the TypeScript compiler throws an error if an object map uses

bigint keys. As a result the generated type for such maps was a JS

Map, creating a runtime/compile time mismatch.



This CL fixes the mismatch by marking int64/uint64 as invalid object

keys so that they will be decoded as JS Maps instead, matching the

runtime behavior to the existing types.

entry.title: Only allow applicable @page properties in computed style.
entry.content:
When PageMarginBoxes are enabled, only allow applicable properties in an

@page context. The list of applicable properties is here:

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-page-3/#page-property-list



I included a few more, highly related properties, e.g. in cases where a

shorthand property is in the list, and new longhands have been added to

specs after this list was created. For instance, we'll allow

background-position-x and background-position-y, since

background-position is in the list (which in turn is part of the

background shorthand).



Also included border-radius properties, and logical properties, such as

padding-inline-start, for instance.



With this change, non-applicable @page properties will no longer be part

of the computed style, and we can revert crrev.com/c/2215323 , which

removed loading of pending resources for @page. We want resources

requested by properties that do apply - such as background-image.

Rename ParameterizedStyleResolverTest NoFetchForAtPage to

FetchForAtPage. The expectation is that the background-image will be

loaded. Add a new NoFetchForAtPage, which uses list-style-image, which

doesn't apply in an @page context.



No behavior changes intended for now. @page computed style is not

web-exposed directly. The only way this can be observed is if it affects

rendering (upcoming CLs).

entry.title: Reland "[OOPIF PDF] Block non-PDF navigation attempts on PDF frames"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 6c12e722cd23ab1afdf90f5848c82472490687fa



The original CL landed a few minutes after commit

18b8ea04764c2378863f60096ce09ce678ebab79, which caused the new tests to

fail. Explicitly enable the RenderDocument feature at a subframe level

only for the tests to make them pass again.



Original change's description:

> [OOPIF PDF] Block non-PDF navigation attempts on PDF frames

>

> Block navigation attempts on PDF frames that aren't relevant for PDF

> viewer setup by blocking the request in PdfNavigationThrottle. That way,

> compromised renderers won't be able to navigate the PDF frames.

>

> To avoid a dependency violation, PdfNavigationThrottle (which lives in

> //components/pdf) uses a new ShouldCancelPdfFrameNavigation() function

> in PdfStreamDelegate that ChromePdfStreamDelegate (which lives in

> //chrome/browser/pdf) overrides to block these navigations.

>

> This is a re-land of https://crrev.com/1262045. The original version,

> rebased, can be seen in the first patchset. This CL adjusts comments to

> match code that has been updated since, changes how PDF content frame

> navigations are blocked to be more specific, and adds more test

> coverage to cover cases where iframes are attached to the PDF embedder

> frame. This avoids breaking any existing extensions that may inject

> subframes into the PDF DOM tree.
